You have 15 HCP and a balanced hand with a five-card spade suit and stoppers in three suits. What do you open?
[BID 1N] With 15 HCP and a balanced 5-3-2-3, open one notrump and describe your strength in one bid; partner takes charge of the level.
[POST-AUCTION]
Partner raised straight to three notrump, giving you about 25 combined points and no eight-card major fit. You'll need nine tricks. Heads up: this one doesn't fit the usual hold-up shape — both defenders hold five hearts, so ducking can't strip either of them. Your real line is your long spades and side aces; cash winners and don't lean on the hold-up here.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You declare three notrump. Your only heart guard is the \HA, but for once the hold-up won't help: West has five hearts too, so ducking never exhausts him. Plan to run spades and clubs for nine.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
A heart lead leaves you with just the \HA between you and a long suit on both sides. Holding up can't break the link here, so take your \HA when it suits you and turn to your real tricks: the long spades and the club \CAJ. Count to nine in the black suits and don't give the lead away carelessly.
[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
With hearts splitting 5-5 against you, the hold-up was a red herring — your tricks always came from spades and clubs. Reading that early and not wasting tempo on a doomed duck was the key. Nicely sorted.
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \H5, fourth-best from your longest suit, hearts JT952. With five hearts of your own you attack the suit you hope to set up.
}
